00:35:57,698 --> 00:35:59,408
And exactly
what idea is that?

969
00:35:59,492 --> 00:36:00,993
Okay.
Don't you understand?

970
00:36:01,077 --> 00:36:02,578
No woman could
compete with you

971
00:36:02,662 --> 00:36:03,996
if she thought
there was even a chance

972
00:36:04,080 --> 00:36:05,081
of you and I
being together.

973
00:36:05,289 --> 00:36:06,499
Really?
No, she blows you away.

974
00:36:06,582 --> 00:36:08,543
Now, get
the hell out and use
the service entrance.

975
00:36:12,129 --> 00:36:13,130
(SIGHS)

976
00:36:13,840 --> 00:36:15,091
Tara, you're here.

977
00:36:16,425 --> 00:36:18,553
Oh, my God.

978
00:36:18,636 --> 00:36:19,846
Louis,

979
00:36:19,929 --> 00:36:21,597
this place
is wonderful.

980
00:36:21,681 --> 00:36:23,015
How long
have you had it?

981
00:36:23,099 --> 00:36:24,976
(CHUCKLES)
I've had it
for generations.

982
00:36:25,059 --> 00:36:27,228
Great Grandma Litt,
she used to make wool

983
00:36:27,770 --> 00:36:29,355
right over there
by the fire.

984
00:36:29,438 --> 00:36:31,107
The natural light
is phenomenal.

985
00:36:32,149 --> 00:36:33,401
Phenomenal.

986
00:36:33,943 --> 00:36:37,780
There's a wildness
to the landscape.
An uninhibited energy.

987
00:36:38,948 --> 00:36:40,074
Wild.

988
00:36:40,783 --> 00:36:42,201
Uninhibited.

989
00:36:43,661 --> 00:36:45,454
It's perfect for us,
Louis.

990
00:36:48,666 --> 00:36:50,084
I'm glad you like it.

991
00:36:50,626 --> 00:36:52,503
I don't just like it.
I love it.

992
00:36:52,837 --> 00:36:54,297
Just like I love you.

993
00:36:58,426 --> 00:36:59,844
Oh, Tara, I love you.

994
00:36:59,927 --> 00:37:01,262
What?

995
00:37:01,679 --> 00:37:02,972
It, your idea.

996
00:37:03,055 --> 00:37:04,056
What you were talking
about earlier?

997
00:37:04,140 --> 00:37:05,349
Which idea?
What happened?

998
00:37:05,433 --> 00:37:06,434
(DOOR OPENS)
Louis, are you okay?

999
00:37:06,517 --> 00:37:08,227
What the hell
is going on here?

1000
00:37:09,061 --> 00:37:10,062
Nothing's going on here.

1001
00:37:10,146 --> 00:37:11,230
What the hell are you
doing in my house?

1002
00:37:11,314 --> 00:37:12,315
Your house?

1003
00:37:12,398 --> 00:37:13,399
Louis, who are
these people?

1004
00:37:13,482 --> 00:37:15,818
These people are the
registered owners
of this property.

1005
00:37:16,819 --> 00:37:19,947
You mean the one you said
had been in your family
for generations?

1006
00:37:20,031 --> 00:37:22,116
That's a lie.
We built this
house ourselves,

1007
00:37:22,199 --> 00:37:24,994
and until five minutes ago,
we were gonna
sell it to him.

1008
00:37:26,746 --> 00:37:28,122
Tara, I can explain.

1009
00:37:28,205 --> 00:37:30,958
I don't need
you to explain.
I've heard enough.

1010
00:37:31,042 --> 00:37:32,251
Tara, wait.

1011
00:37:32,335 --> 00:37:33,544
Please.

1012
00:37:34,337 --> 00:37:35,338
Tara, please wait.

1013
00:37:35,421 --> 00:37:38,007
You know, I've heard
about people like you.

1014
00:37:38,507 --> 00:37:40,051
You're trying
to get free design
work out of me

1015
00:37:40,134 --> 00:37:42,595
so you can decide
whether or not you want
to buy this house.

1016
00:37:42,762 --> 00:37:43,930
That has nothing
to do with it.

1017
00:37:44,013 --> 00:37:45,348
Really? Because first,

1018
00:37:45,431 --> 00:37:46,557
you tried to get me
to work on this

1019
00:37:46,641 --> 00:37:48,142
without even
seeing the space.

1020
00:37:48,225 --> 00:37:49,936
Then you lured me out here
under false pretenses.

1021
00:37:50,019 --> 00:37:52,688
So, why don't you
tell me what exactly
is going on here?

1022
00:37:52,772 --> 00:37:54,523
I lied to you
about owning a house
in the Hamptons

1023
00:37:54,607 --> 00:37:56,192
so I could spend
time with you.

1024
00:37:57,652 --> 00:37:59,987
What? Why?
Why would you do that?

1025
00:38:00,071 --> 00:38:01,656
Because you are perfect,

1026
00:38:01,739 --> 00:38:03,032
and beautiful,

1027
00:38:03,783 --> 00:38:05,034
and intelligent,

1028
00:38:05,326 --> 00:38:06,911
and talented.

1029
00:38:06,994 --> 00:38:09,830
And so far
out of my league

1030
00:38:10,915 --> 00:38:12,833
it was the only thing
that I could come up with

1031
00:38:12,917 --> 00:38:15,503
to find the time I needed
to make you fall for me.

1032
00:38:16,504 --> 00:38:18,464
You were willing
to buy and remodel

1033
00:38:18,547 --> 00:38:20,049
an entire house
to do that?

1034
00:38:21,133 --> 00:38:22,301
I was.

1035
00:38:22,843 --> 00:38:25,930
That's the most
romantic thing
I've ever heard.

1036
00:38:27,348 --> 00:38:28,557
Really?

1037
00:38:29,892 --> 00:38:31,560
Yeah. Yes, really.
(CHUCKLES)

1038
00:38:33,354 --> 00:38:35,314
Tara, would you like
to have dinner with me?

1039
00:38:36,482 --> 00:38:38,234
I'd love to, Louis.

1040
00:38:39,777 --> 00:38:41,112
(BOTH CHUCKLE)

1041
00:38:49,412 --> 00:38:51,455
RACHEL:
What are you working on?

1042
00:38:51,539 --> 00:38:52,748
An engagement letter.

1043
00:38:54,166 --> 00:38:55,167
You got a new client.

1044
00:38:55,251 --> 00:38:56,752
I got us two new clients.

1045
00:38:58,170 --> 00:39:00,339
So, that's what you had
to do the other day.

1046
00:39:00,423 --> 00:39:02,008
Well, something like that.

1047
00:39:02,091 --> 00:39:04,301
The one I got the other day
led to the one I got today.

1048
00:39:05,720 --> 00:39:06,887
That's great.

1049
00:39:07,263 --> 00:39:08,681
Yeah, what's
on your mind?

1050
00:39:12,226 --> 00:39:15,146
I know you said
that you'd give me
an hour of your time

1051
00:39:15,229 --> 00:39:17,398
later this week,
but I need
that hour tonight.

1052
00:39:18,024 --> 00:39:19,608
Rachel, it's been
a long day.

1053
00:39:19,692 --> 00:39:20,985
Can we talk about this
in the morning?

1054
00:39:21,068 --> 00:39:22,403
No, Jessica, we can't.

1055
00:39:25,322 --> 00:39:27,533
Leonard Bailey's
execution date's been set.

1056
00:39:29,827 --> 00:39:32,621
And I don't know
how to tell a man
that he's going to die.

1057
00:39:40,254 --> 00:39:43,632
You know, I always knew
that Jill and I were
from two different worlds.

1058
00:39:45,968 --> 00:39:47,428
I mean,
she was a Sutter

1059
00:39:48,304 --> 00:39:49,263
and I was just...

1060
00:39:49,346 --> 00:39:52,141
A guy who was good
with numbers
and didn't have much else.

1061
00:39:54,935 --> 00:39:56,228
I figured it was only
a matter of time

1062
00:39:56,312 --> 00:39:57,938
before she came
to her senses.

1063
00:39:59,315 --> 00:40:00,483
But she never did.

1064
00:40:01,525 --> 00:40:02,902
And let me guess.

1065
00:40:03,527 --> 00:40:05,154
William never
accepted it.

1066
00:40:06,655 --> 00:40:09,825
So, when he asked me
to develop that algorithm,
I thought...

1067
00:40:10,493 --> 00:40:11,952
This was my chance.

1068
00:40:13,412 --> 00:40:16,332
And when I gave it to him,
he acted so proud.

1069
00:40:17,166 --> 00:40:19,210
Started calling me
his genius son-in-law.

1070
00:40:20,586 --> 00:40:22,338
But I was really just
the world's biggest sucker,

1071
00:40:22,421 --> 00:40:23,464
because I let that
son of a bitch

1072
00:40:23,547 --> 00:40:24,590
get one over on me

1073
00:40:24,673 --> 00:40:27,176
and I'll regret it
for the rest of my life.

1074
00:40:29,345 --> 00:40:31,972
What if you could get
one over on him?

1075
00:40:33,766 --> 00:40:35,810
What are you
talking about?

1076
00:40:38,104 --> 00:40:39,980
You said yourself
they offered you a deal.

1077
00:40:40,064 --> 00:40:41,565
I bet they'd
still take it.

1078
00:40:41,649 --> 00:40:42,691
No way.

1079
00:40:43,192 --> 00:40:44,985
If I give them him,
they go after her.

1080
00:40:45,069 --> 00:40:47,738
Not if you get them
to give Jill
immunity first.

1081
00:40:47,822 --> 00:40:48,948
No.
Kevin, you have to.

1082
00:40:49,031 --> 00:40:50,324
It's too big a risk.

1083
00:40:51,659 --> 00:40:52,952
And, and you're my
father-in-law's lawyer.

1084
00:40:53,035 --> 00:40:54,036
You can't even be
saying this to me.

1085
00:40:54,120 --> 00:40:55,121
I am nobody's lawyer.

1086
00:40:55,204 --> 00:40:56,413
I am your friend,
and I am saying...

1087
00:40:56,497 --> 00:40:57,832
Well, my answer's no.

1088
00:40:57,915 --> 00:40:59,166
And I want your
word right now

1089
00:40:59,250 --> 00:41:00,960
that you won't tell
anyone what I told you.

1090
00:41:01,043 --> 00:41:02,378
Kevin, please...
Mike, I'm serious.

1091
00:41:02,461 --> 00:41:06,048
No one can
ever know anything
about what I told you.

1092
00:41:09,718 --> 00:41:11,053
You have my word.

1093
00:41:20,062 --> 00:41:22,231
Did I ever tell you
my mother was a teacher?

1094
00:41:23,816 --> 00:41:25,234
First grade.

1095
00:41:26,986 --> 00:41:30,114
Everybody always said
she was the best teacher
their kid ever had.

1096
00:41:31,073 --> 00:41:32,324
And she loved it.

1097
00:41:34,493 --> 00:41:37,997
But she also always
dreamed of seeing Spain
when she retired.

1098
00:41:39,540 --> 00:41:41,500
That was supposed
to be six years ago.

1099
00:41:42,543 --> 00:41:44,128
But then the
State Teachers
Pension fund

1100
00:41:44,211 --> 00:41:46,005
decided to invest
its money with

1101
00:41:46,922 --> 00:41:48,382
William Sutter.

1102
00:41:51,886 --> 00:41:54,847
She died last year,
still working.

1103
00:41:56,015 --> 00:41:57,266
And every year,
I tried to pay
for her trip,

1104
00:41:57,349 --> 00:41:58,934
but she just
wouldn't let me.

1105
00:41:59,393 --> 00:42:01,228
Sean, why are you
telling me this?

1106
00:42:01,645 --> 00:42:04,982
Because the judge decided
to rule on your motion
to dismiss after all.

1107
00:42:06,442 --> 00:42:08,402
Which means
we're out of time.

1108
00:42:08,485 --> 00:42:10,779
And you didn't just
come here to tell me
about your mother.

1109
00:42:13,365 --> 00:42:14,450
No.

1110
00:42:15,451 --> 00:42:17,620
I came here to ask
for that trading program.

